Golang is a perfectly fine language if you do NOT need modularity.  If you need to load and unload shared objects (DLL/.so files) then Go won't work.  At all.  It'll just crash when you go to unload loaded shared objects.  This is due to how Go coroutines function.  If you've ever wondered why Go binaries are single binary files, this is why.  For a transpiled language like Typescript, where it's of general irrelevance as a language because it still has to generate Javascript at the end of the day and most people use it as-is, rewriting it in Go is fine.

I was initially disappointed it wasn't written in C# (C# is love, C# is life), but upon thinking about it further, I think that wouldn't have been the best choice. C# compiles to native code at runtime, which means there's always a small delay at the start of executing a program. If your program is a long-running program like a GUI tool or a game, that tiny delay is a total non-issue, but if your tool is a compiler designed to be run frequently, that delay could be a significant issue. That is, unless the JIT'd machine code is cached? I'm not sure ü§î
